metadata.name: √âSSERS #71
metadata.description:
Human beings, living beings, existences.

Made of the same fundamental matter, instincts and drives.
The same basic frailties, hopes and dreams.

Meanwhile, we manage to shine in our own way. 
We build our own voice, particular, unrepeatable.
We cast a light, and a shadow, just like no other.

Swinging between these two realities we dance, 
playing the game of joining and splitting.

-

"√âSSERS" attempts to suggest and evocate this dynamic equilibrium.
Basic colors, shapes and compositions that, despite being fundamentally the same, reclaim their distinctive identity and temperament.

-

Key features:

- 12 color palettes + background color
- 3 Symmetry levels
- 3 Vertex distribution modes
- # of polygons
- # of grid subdivisions

Secondary features provide additional variation.


Enter live mode and press "s" to download high resolution image ( 4200x5940 px ).

Works best in desktop and laptop computers. It may take several seconds to run on handheld devices.

-

Coded in p5js, with love.

metadata.name: Takashi's Death #247
metadata.description:
Akira by Katsuhiro Otomo.
A global landmark in the shaping of the Cyberpunk genre, and a watershed title for the medium.

I got my hands on the tank≈çbon(s) more than 20 years ago and those pages upon pages at the end of the third one depicting the destruction of Neo-Tokyo stayed with me ever since. Pages of stunning destruction, leaving me in awe.

This is my generative take on the subject. An attempt to evoke the power of that one panel in a cohesive collection.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more info on the composition here : https://ulucode.com/wp/takashis-death/

Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels ( height ). I recommend starting with "4".

More features are available, but a decent GPU is recommended:
- Press "space" to toggle an animation on/off
- Press "u" to Unlock the camera. You can then :
. Mouse left : Rotate
. Mouse middle/wheel : Zoom
. Mouse right : Translate
. "r" : reset camera
. "a" : change antialiasing quality : 3 settings in rotation. Try this if your framerate is too low.

metadata.name: Memory Module #241
metadata.description:
Day by day, memories accumulate and shape our dreams, subconscious, ideals, and ultimately, the innermost self. 

This artwork is created by repeatedly drawing squares that are identical in size, with each one representing a memory. As new memories form, the older ones become obscured, fuzzy, or joined with others to form belief structures and intuitions. I hope that this work will remind you of someone, someplace, a song or a melody that‚Äôs important to you. 

Keyboard controls:
[S] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[G] Toggle paper texture.

URL params:
aspect: custom aspect ratio (?aspect=3).
res: custom resolution multiplier (?res=4).

Made with fractal math and p5js, Memory Module is the first in a 5-part generative art series about introspection. You can read more about the series here: https://elsifthen.github.io/

Created by elsif, 2022.07.

metadata.name: Gen22: Personalized Generative Fashion #72
metadata.description:
Gen22 is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022.

The Gen22 system is a provocation for the future of personalized generative fashion, combining culture, history, and technology through multiple generative algorithms to produce a personalized garment complete with a weaving pattern for the tartan textile and sewing pattern for the generative garment.

The system generates a tartan textile design, a generative tunic design and a personalized sewing pattern in the needed size of the user. The weaving key of the textile pattern and the construction pattern can be used by weavers and sewists in order to produce the physical textile and garment locally.

The tunic pattern created is generated from a parametric pattern system able to create 3,125 different garment patterns in 15 sizes, to produce a specific unique textile and garment for the user.

-- Interaction --

Click ( Desktop Browsers Only )- Uses the x position of the mouse click and changes the size of the 2D garment pattern from 0 (leftmost screen) to 15 (rightmost screen)
Double-click or double tap - generates a PDF of the garment and textile patterns
Click or Tap on Textile patterns - updates the current pattern

-- Recommendations --

While we‚Äôve worked to adapt the project to many screen sizes, Gen22 looks best on laptop and desktop monitors. The interaction and PDF generation generally works better on desktop or laptop.

-- Artists --

Elizabeth Bigger - Computational Fashion Designer and Researcher  -  https://elizabethbigger.com/
Luis Fraguada - Creative Developer - https://linktr.ee/fraguada
GenCloth - https://gencloth.com

-- References --

Elizabeth Esther Bigger and Luis Edgardo Fraguada. 2016. Programmable plaid: The search for seamless integration in fashion and technology.. In Proceedings of the 2016 ACM International Joint Conference on Pervasive and Ubiquitous Computing: Adjunct(UbiComp ‚Äô16). Association for Computing Machinery, Heidelberg, Germany, 464‚Äì469. https://doi.org/10.1145/2968219.2971343

metadata.name: Inertia #26
metadata.description:
This project will be reserved and free for 48 hours, for all the holders of any of my projects!

The amount of reserves for each user will be equal to the amount of all the token held at 13:00 CEST [UTC+2] (May 23)
(example: user holds 3 "Figment" and 2 "ACCUMULATOR", will be able to mint "Inertia" 5 times)

48h from now I will update the reserves list and burn the remaining tokens

WARINING: The reserves will expire 48h after the drop! And a price for the unlocked mintables will be set (unreserved mints will not be free).

---

"Inertia is a property of matter by which it continues in its existing state of rest or uniform motion in a straight line, unless that state is changed by an external force."

Particles are blasted from 2 to 4 sides of the canvas, each particle has its own mass and it has to traverse a friction-field, once it loses its momentum completely it stops and leaves a trace, adding or subtracting light from the canvas.

The friction-field has 18 possible mutation kinds.
Mutations are high-friction zones of various shapes.

Made just with JS on a canvas
right-click to save

metadata.name: primordial soup #118
metadata.description:
1024 kinematic automata that imitate living organisms, leaving behind a trace of paint before going extinct. Blotches of paint are deposited by these nodes that attract and repulse each other according to rules based on their color and size.

Short description of features:
- mood: the palette
- tone: the noisiness
- flow: the number of neighbors affecting each node
- brow: the brush size
- delirium: brush modifier
- distancing: kinetic rule modifier

Each feature is equally likely - rarity is in the eye of the beholder.

@balidani

metadata.name: walkinthepark #136
metadata.description:
Mazes are almost entierly context-free. The mazes of `walkinthepark` have no entrance or exit. Not all of them are solvable. Any resemblance to reality is pure coincidence.

All features are distributed equally:
- weave - The internal pattern of sub-mazes.
- density - The density of the sub-mazes.
- color - Yep.
- aim - How big the biggest sub-maze can get.
- bars - How connected sub-mazes are.
- stroke - The randomness of lines.
- skew - How much some sub-mazes are rotated.
- grain - How many sub-mazes are rotated.

@balidani, Dec 2021

metadata.name: Nil #107
metadata.description:
A balanced combination of spatial subdivision and algorithm sonification. A subdivision surface algorithm is¬†recursive¬†in nature: the process starts with a base level of area, and a refinement scheme is then applied to this field. This process takes that element and subdivides it, creating new segmented areas. The positions of the new areas are computed based on the positions of nearby old fields, edges, and/or faces. A cellular automata is running on the texture of some of these areas, building continuous, tautological worlds of binary patterns and relationships. Thus, unfolding of a pixel‚Äôs ‚Äòumwelt‚Äô can be witnessed through the slow, contemplative process.

The audio synthesis consists of a stochastic melody that emerges along the division of the new areas and territories within the image structure. This melody is complemented with tiny micro sounds, triggered by each new generation of the surface mounted cellular automata. 

Touch to listen
